  state/

data/research_radar/
content/research-radar/
layouts/research-radar/
```

## Setup

```bash
cd /Users/ziye/@Workspace/Homepage/ziye-homepage
python3 -m venv .venv
source .venv/bin/activate
pip install -e ./research-radar
```

## Usage

Run a recent update with the default config window:

```bash
research-radar update
```

Backfill a specific range:

```bash
research-radar backfill --start-date 2025-01-01 --end-date 2025-03-31
```

Rebuild JSON outputs from the current SQLite store only:

```bash
research-radar export
```

You can override locations when needed:

```bash
research-radar update \
  --config ./research-radar/topics.yaml \
  --state-path ./research-radar/state/papers.sqlite3 \
  --data-dir ./data/research_radar
```

## Configuration

The sample configuration lives at `research-radar/topics.yaml`.

It defines:

- source fetch settings
- watch queries and local filters
- topic buckets and priorities
- tracked keywords for trends
- export limits and rising-keyword windows

## Testing

The test suite uses the standard library `unittest` runner:

```bash
PYTHONPATH=./research-radar/src python3 -m unittest discover -s research-radar/tests
```

## Notes

- `research-radar/state/papers.sqlite3` is created on the first successful run.
- `data/research_radar/*.json` is safe to commit; Hugo reads those files directly.
- The GitHub Actions workflow at `.github/workflows/research-radar.yaml` runs the same CLI on a schedule and commits refreshed data.
